```javascript
function getTextItems(textContent) {
  return textContent.items.map((val) => val.str);
}

function searchQuery(textItems, query, options) {
  const textJoined = textItems.join(" ");
  const regexFlags = ["g"];
  if (options.ignoreCase) regexFlags.push("i");
  let fquery = query.trim();
  if (options.completeWords) fquery = `\\b${fquery}\\b`;
  const regex = new RegExp(fquery, regexFlags.join(""));
  const matches = [];
  let match;
  while ((match = regex.exec(textJoined)) !== null)
    matches.push([match.index, match[0].length, match[0]]);
  return matches;
}
```

**The `searchQuery` function treats the `query` as a single regex pattern!** It creates a `RegExp(fquery, "g")` from the query string. This means:
- A single string query can be a regex with `|` operator to match multiple patterns
- E.g., `"hello|world"` would match both "hello" and "world"

